.TH "vpn\-switch" "1" "May 2026" "" "VPN connection manager"
.SH NAME
vpn\-switch \(em POSIX\-shell VPN connection manager for FreeBSD and
Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] [\f[I]command\f[R]] [\f[I]arguments\f[R]\&...]
.PP
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]help\f[R] [\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]bootstrap\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
\f[I]profile\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]start\f[R] \f[I]config\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]stop\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]sync\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]version\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]validate\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]inspect\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]session\f[R] \f[I]subcommand\f[R]
[\f[I]name\f[R] | \f[I]PID\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[B]wireguard\f[R]|\f[B]openvpn\f[R]
\f[I]subcommand\f[R] [\f[I]arguments\f[R]\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] is a POSIX\-shell\-based connection manager for
WireGuard and OpenVPN.
It organises VPN configurations as a filesystem database (directories
group configurations by purpose, symlinks express defaults and named
sessions) and automates firewall and DNS integration via composable
phase scripts.
.PP
The tool follows a combinator architecture: every command is one of
three function types (terminal, combinator, batch combinator), each
outputs the next rewrite step rather than executing side effects
directly, and a small set of interpreters controls execution.
The result is dry\-run\-by\-default behaviour for terminals and a deeply
inspectable command pipeline.
See \f[B]ARCHITECTURE.md\f[R] for the full design rationale.
.PP
After installation (see \f[B]gmake install\f[R], \f[B]INSTALL.md\f[R]),
initialise a per\-user database with \f[B]vpn\-switch bootstrap\f[R],
then \f[B]import\f[R], \f[B]add\f[R], and \f[B]start\f[R] VPN
configurations through the commands documented below.
.SS Concepts
.TP
\f[B]Database\f[R]
A per\-user directory (default \f[I]$HOME/.vpn\-switch/db\f[R]) holding
imported configurations, environment overrides, active and saved
sessions, and logs.
Created once via \f[B]bootstrap\f[R], kept in sync with the installed
source via \f[B]sync\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Configuration\f[R]
A static \f[I].conf\f[R] (WireGuard) or \f[I].ovpn\f[R] (OpenVPN) file
imported into the database.
Lives under \f[I]wireguard/\f[R] or \f[I]openvpn/\f[R], optionally
grouped in subdirectories via \f[B]add\f[R] and \f[B]link\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Patch\f[R]
Provider configuration files are typically written for Linux \(em a
WireGuard \f[I].conf\f[R], for example, embeds
\f[I]PostUp\f[R]/\f[I]PostDown\f[R] hooks that call Linux\(cqs
\f[I]resolvconf\f[R].
vpn\-switch never runs the imported file as\-is: at \f[B]start\f[R] it
patches a session copy \(em stripping those Linux\-specific DNS hooks
(DNS is handled by the \f[I]dns\f[R] phase instead) and, for OpenVPN,
injecting the up/down scripts, daemon mode and interface \(em so one
config works on FreeBSD and Linux alike.
Preview the result with \f[B]<proto> patch\f[R] \f[I]config\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Session\f[R]
A runtime instance of a started VPN \(em one Unix process plus its
metadata directory under \f[I].session/<PID>/\f[R] (interface, protocol,
cached connect/disconnect scripts).
Sessions can be saved by \f[B]name\f[R] for later resumption via
\f[B]session start <name>\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Phase\f[R]
A composable step in the connect/disconnect script (typically
\f[I]firewall\f[R], \f[I]vpn\f[R], \f[I]dns\f[R]), run in order on
connect and in reverse on disconnect.
Each phase is generated from a swappable \f[B]backend\f[R] (firewall:
\f[I]pf\f[R]/\f[I]ipfw\f[R]/\f[I]iptables\f[R]/\f[I]none\f[R]; dns:
\f[I]resolvconf\f[R]/\f[I]unbound\f[R]/\f[I]djbdns\f[R]/\f[I]dnsmasq\f[R]/\f[I]none\f[R]),
selected per phase via a \f[I]phase:backend\f[R] syntax in
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_PHASES_CONNECT\f[R] /
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_PHASES_DISCONNECT\f[R].
Custom backends can be added from a template, so sophisticated setups
can trigger whatever extra actions they need.
See \f[B]vpn\-switch help phases\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Profile\f[R]
A predefined set of environment defaults installed by
\f[B]bootstrap\f[R].
\f[I]minimal\f[R] covers the essential interpreters and safe display
defaults; \f[I]all\f[R] installs the full interpreter set for broader
compatibility.
.SS Command syntax
The canonical form is \f[B]vpn\-switch\f[R] \f[I]<object>\f[R]
\f[I]<verb>\f[R] [\f[I]args\f[R]], where \f[I]object\f[R] is
\f[B]wireguard\f[R], \f[B]openvpn\f[R], \f[B]session\f[R],
\f[B]logs\f[R], \f[B]phases\f[R], \f[B]env\f[R], \f[B]environment\f[R],
\f[B]database\f[R], etc.:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch wireguard import \(ti/server.conf
vpn\-switch session save work
vpn\-switch logs clean
.EE
.PP
A small set of top\-level \f[I]<verb>\f[R]\-only shortcuts is provided
for the most common operations.
Each delegates to one or more object\-verb forms:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch start <config>     \->  wireguard start | openvpn start
vpn\-switch stop               \->  wireguard stop + openvpn stop (batch)
vpn\-switch sync               \->  phases sync + env sync + version sync
vpn\-switch validate           \->  all <object> validate (batch)
vpn\-switch inspect            \->  all <object> inspect (batch)
.EE
.PP
Use the shortcut when the \f[I]object\f[R] is obvious or you want the
bundled behaviour; use the explicit \f[I]object verb\f[R] form when you
need protocol\- or subsystem\-specific control.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Without a database
The only commands that run without an existing database.
Start here on a fresh install.
.TP
\f[B]bootstrap <path> <profile>\f[R]
Create a new database at <path> with the named profile
.TP
\f[B]help [<subcommand>]\f[R]
Show top\-level help, or help for a command group or topic
.SS Connection
Bring tunnels up and down, and keep the database in sync with the
source.
.TP
\f[B]stop\f[R]
Stop every active VPN session (idempotent)
.TP
\f[B]sync\f[R]
Refresh the database from installed source templates
.TP
\f[B]version\f[R]
Report the database and source SHAs (drift means run `sync')
.TP
\f[B]start [<config>]\f[R]
Connect using a config; with no argument, resume the default session or
pick at random
.SS Sessions
A session is one started VPN instance: a process plus its
\&.session/<PID>/ metadata.
Save, resume, inspect and reconcile them.
.TP
\f[B]session disconnect <PID>\f[R]
Lower\-level disconnect of a session by PID (no name resolution)
.TP
\f[B]session stop [<name>|<PID>]\f[R]
Stop an active session; with no argument, stop all active sessions
.TP
\f[B]session list\f[R]
Show all active and saved sessions
.TP
\f[B]session show [<name>|<PID>]\f[R]
Show a session\(cqs cached connect script and metadata
.TP
\f[B]session remove <name>|<PID>\f[R]
Remove a stopped session from the database
.TP
\f[B]session start [<name>|<PID>]\f[R]
Resume a saved session by replaying its cached connect script
.TP
\f[B]session save [<name>]\f[R]
Save the most\-recent session under a name for later resumption
.TP
\f[B]session clean\f[R]
Generate cleanup commands for stale/orphaned sessions
.TP
\f[B]session refresh\f[R]
Reconcile interface ownership with the loaded peers
.TP
\f[B]session help\f[R]
Show session\-management command help
.TP
\f[B]Reserved Session Keywords\f[R]
latest \- system\-managed ownership pointer, updated on each start
default \- user\-managed, set via `session save' with no name
.SS Protocol\-specific (wireguard, openvpn)
Manage configurations, groups and tunnels for both \f[B]wireguard\f[R]
and \f[B]openvpn\f[R].
The two subcommands share the same shape; substitute either where
\f[I]<proto>\f[R] appears.
.TP
\f[B]<proto> start [<category>]\f[R]
Start a WireGuard tunnel; with no argument, use the default or a random
config
.TP
\f[B]<proto> stop [<interface>]\f[R]
Stop WireGuard sessions, or one specific interface
.TP
\f[B]<proto> import <file>\f[R]
Import a WireGuard .conf file into the database
.TP
\f[B]<proto> list [<category>]\f[R]
List WireGuard configs and categories
.TP
\f[B]<proto> add <category> [<config> [<alias>]]\f[R]
Create a category, or link a config into one
.TP
\f[B]<proto> link <alias> <target>\f[R]
Create a protocol\-level alias to a config
.TP
\f[B]<proto> remove <name>\f[R]
Remove a config, link or category (with safety checks)
.TP
\f[B]<proto> validate\f[R]
Check WireGuard symlink integrity in the database
.TP
\f[B]<proto> clean [<category>]\f[R]
Generate cleanup commands for broken links
.TP
\f[B]<proto> patch <config>\f[R]
Preview the patched config that would be used to connect
.TP
\f[B]<proto> info <category>\f[R]
Show category details, including config expiry dates
.TP
\f[B]<proto> dump\f[R]
Generate restorable shell commands for all WireGuard configs
.TP
\f[B]<proto> help\f[R]
Show WireGuard command help
.SS Database lifecycle
Back up, restore and refresh the database itself.
.TP
\f[B]phases sync [<phase>]\f[R]
Refresh phase scripts (firewall, vpn, dns) from source templates
.TP
\f[B]env sync\f[R]
Refresh environment defaults in .env/default/ from source templates
.TP
\f[B]version sync\f[R]
Stamp the database\(cqs .version with the source\(cqs current SHA
.TP
\f[B]dump\f[R]
Export the database as an executable shell script
.TP
\f[B]batch <file>\f[R]
Execute a file of vpn\-switch commands line by line
.TP
\f[B]restore <file>\f[R]
Restore the database from a previously\-generated dump file
.SS Configuration
Read and change vpn\-switch environment variables.
.TP
\f[B]environment cache [on|off|status]\f[R]
Manage the cached\-environment optimisation
.TP
\f[B]setenv <VAR> <VALUE>\f[R]
Set a vpn\-switch environment variable (writes to .env/local/)
.TP
\f[B]getenv <VAR>\f[R]
Print the effective value of a variable with its source
.TP
\f[B]unsetenv <VAR>\f[R]
Remove a variable from .env/local/
.TP
\f[B]printenv [<VAR>]\f[R]
Show all effective environment variables, or just one
.TP
\f[B]environment inspect\f[R]
Show the environment resolution chain (default \-> local \-> cache)
.SS Diagnostics
Inspect current state and check health.
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Show a brief status of the active VPN and its interfaces
.TP
\f[B]inspect\f[R]
Full descriptive state dump (sessions, configs, phases, system)
.TP
\f[B]logs validate\f[R]
Check for old log files beyond the retention period
.TP
\f[B]logs clean\f[R]
Generate rm commands for old logs (review, then pipe to sh)
.TP
\f[B]validate\f[R]
Health check: run all sub\-checks; non\-zero exit on critical issues
.TP
\f[B]Individual validate sub\-checks\f[R]
Each check of `validate' is also runnable alone for focused output,
e.g.: install validate, version validate, sudo validate, network
validate, database validate, binaries validate, permissions validate,
environment validate, phases validate.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_BASE\f[R]
Path to the database directory.
Default: \f[I]$HOME/.vpn\-switch/db\f[R].
Each user typically has their own database.
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_LIBDIR\f[R]
Path to the installed library directory (include/, template/).
Set by the installer (sed\-patched into the script).
Default if unset: \f[I]/usr/local/lib/vpn\-switch\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_TERMINAL_INTERPRETER\f[R]
How terminal functions\(cq output is processed.
Default: \f[B]cat\f[R] (display without executing \(em safe by default).
Set to \f[B]sh\f[R] to auto\-execute.
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_COMBINATOR_INTERPRETER\f[R], \f[B]VPN_SWITCH_BATCH_COMBINATOR_INTERPRETER\f[R]
Interpreters for combinator and batch\-combinator output.
Defaults recurse through the dispatcher; rarely need overriding.
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_INTERPRETER_\f[R]\f[I]<function>\f[R]
Per\-function interpreter overrides.
Highest priority in the resolution chain.
Used for dry\-run inspection (set to \f[B]cat\f[R]), logging, or
privilege escalation (set to \f[B]sudo sh\f[R]).
See \f[B]TUTORIAL_SUDO.md\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_PHASES_CONNECT\f[R], \f[B]VPN_SWITCH_PHASES_DISCONNECT\f[R]
Ordered list of phases to run on connect/disconnect.
Defaults: \(lqfirewall vpn dns\(rq and \(lqdns vpn firewall\(rq
respectively.
Set to omit phases (e.g.\ \(lqvpn\(rq alone skips firewall and DNS
integration).
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_INTERFACE_wireguard\f[R], \f[B]VPN_SWITCH_INTERFACE_openvpn\f[R]
Interface names for each protocol.
Defaults: \f[B]wg0\f[R] and \f[B]tun0\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_RETENTION_DAYS_LOG\f[R], \f[B]VPN_SWITCH_RETENTION_DAYS_TRACE\f[R]
Days to retain log/trace files.
Default: 1.
Set to 0 to disable logging.
Higher values useful during debugging.
.TP
\f[B]VPN_SWITCH_FUNCTION_OVERRIDE\f[R]
Path to a shell file sourced after core modules.
Allows replacing any function (test mocks, local customisations).
See \f[B]ARCHITECTURE.md\f[R].
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/bin/vpn\-switch\f[R]
The main script (location varies with install \f[B]PREFIX\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/sbin/{wg,ovpn}\-resolvconf\-{up,down}\f[R]
DNS helper scripts (FreeBSD\-specific; path hardcoded by phase scripts).
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/lib/vpn\-switch/include/*.sh\f[R]
Shell module library (sourced at runtime via
\f[I]VPN_SWITCH_LIBDIR\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/lib/vpn\-switch/template/\f[R]
Templates: environment defaults, phase scripts, platform variables,
\f[I]VERSION\f[R] marker.
.TP
\f[B]/usr/local/share/doc/vpn\-switch/\f[R]
Installed documentation (\f[I]README.md\f[R], \f[I]LICENSE\f[R],
\f[I]QUICK_REFERENCE.md\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]$VPN_SWITCH_BASE/\f[R]
Per\-user database (sessions, configurations, environment overrides,
logs).
Default: \f[I]$HOME/.vpn\-switch/db\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]$VPN_SWITCH_BASE/.env/local/\f[R]
Per\-user environment overrides.
Highest priority.
Edit via \f[B]setenv\f[R] rather than directly.
.TP
\f[B]$VPN_SWITCH_BASE/.session/<PID>/\f[R]
Active VPN session metadata (interface, protocol, original config,
cached connect/disconnect scripts).
.TP
\f[B]$VPN_SWITCH_BASE/session/<name>\f[R]
Symlinks naming saved sessions for resumption.
.TP
\f[B]$VPN_SWITCH_BASE/.log/YYYY\-MM\-DD/\f[R]
Per\-day log and trace files.
Subject to retention via the *RETENTION_DAYS_** variables.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success, no findings.
.TP
\f[B]non\-zero\f[R]
For \f[B]validate\f[R]: critical findings detected (count of issues,
capped).
For other commands: command\-specific failure.
.SH EXAMPLES
Bootstrap a per\-user database and verify the install:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch bootstrap \(ti/.vpn\-switch/db minimal
vpn\-switch validate
.EE
.PP
Import a config, group it, and connect:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch wireguard import \(ti/Downloads/wg\-CH\-12.conf
vpn\-switch wireguard add privacy wg\-CH\-12 switzerland
vpn\-switch start switzerland
.EE
.PP
Save the live session by name, then resume later:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch session save work
vpn\-switch stop
vpn\-switch session start work
.EE
.PP
Inspect what a command would do, without executing:
.IP
.EX
vpn\-switch setenv VPN_SWITCH_INTERPRETER_start cat
vpn\-switch start switzerland
# Output: the next\-rewrite\-step command, not its result.
.EE
.PP
After upgrading vpn\-switch source, refresh the database:
.IP
.EX
sudo gmake install
vpn\-switch sync
vpn\-switch version
.EE
